Phase 7 — Notifications
Service: notification-service · MongoDB `notifications` db, consuming
RabbitMQ `order.placed` / `order.cancelled` (queue `notification.order-placed`,
per ARCHITECTURE.md §5)

Last phase because it's a pure consumer of events Phases 5 and 6 already
produce — nothing here can be built or meaningfully tested before an
order can actually be placed and cancelled. See
Archive/Development/Backend/Discussion/Stage-1 Q1 for what this phase
does and does not do (records only, no outbound delivery — NTF-004).

Scenarios covered: 24, 25, 26, 27, 28.

---

## Scenarios 24, 25 — event consumption (not an HTTP endpoint)

NTF-001: an `order.placed` event triggers a recorded notification.
NTF-002: an `order.cancelled` event triggers a recorded notification.

Consumed message (illustrative shape, from order-service's publish in
Phase 5/6 — the exact payload is order-service's contract to define, not
notification-service's; shown here for traceability only):
```json
{
  "orderId": "20000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001",
  "accountId": "aaaaaaaa-aaaa-4aaa-8aaa-aaaaaaaaaaaa",
  "eventType": "ORDER_PLACED",
  "occurredAt": "2026-07-13T14:00:00Z"
}
```

Resulting document (matches Archive/Development/Database §4.1 and the
data already seeded non-interactively in Database-Scripts step 10):
```json
{
  "_id": "40000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001",
  "accountId": "aaaaaaaa-aaaa-4aaa-8aaa-aaaaaaaaaaaa",
  "orderId": "20000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001",
  "type": "ORDER_PLACED",
  "message": "Your order has been placed.",
  "createdAt": "2026-07-13T14:00:01Z"
}
```

Scenario 28 — NTF-005: if the insert above fails (Mongo unreachable,
whatever the cause), the message must go to the dead-letter exchange
(ARCHITECTURE.md §5) rather than being silently dropped or retried
forever, but this must never reach back into order-service — the order is
already committed and final by the time this consumer even sees the
event.

